    • Method Detail

      • addAll

        public void addAll​(T[] array)
        Inserts all of the elements in the specified array into this list in the order the items appear in the array, starting at the head of the list. Shifts the element currently at that position (if any) and any subsequent elements to the right (increases their indices). The new elements will appear in the list in the order that they were in the array
        Parameters:
        array - containing elements to be added to this list
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the array is null

      • clear

        public void clear()
        Removes all of the elements from this list. The list will be empty (except the dummy head node) after this call returns.

      • subListReverse

        public void subListReverse​(int fromIndex,
                           int toIndex)
        If the list is empty, print the message "The list is empty" Check the indexes to ensure -fromIndex is not less than 0 -toIndex is not greater than size -fromIndex is less than toIndex
        Parameters:
        fromIndex - Representing the index to start printing from in reverse order (this value will be the last item printed)
        toIndex - Representing the index to stop printing from in reverse order (this value will be the first item printed)
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if one of the indexes are incorrect meaning the fromIndex is greater than the toIndex otherwise print the nodes fromIndex to toIndex in reverse order or the toIndex is greater than size Note you will need to write a private method called subListReverse that is overloaded from the initial call from main. This method will need additional parameters
